===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|der||small animal, deer|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|deor|dēor|animal|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|deuzan||lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|dʰeusóm|living thing}} (compare {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|dash|ram|lang=sq}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|daũsos||upper air; heaven|lang=lt}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|title=|dʰeus|breath}}- (compare {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|dùsti|to sigh|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|душа|breath, spirit||tr=dušá|lang=ru}}), full-grade derivative of {{proto|Indo-European|title=|dʰu̯ésmi}} (compare {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|dvėsti||to breath, exhale|lang=lt}}, Russian {{term|||to cough|tr=dvochat'|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term||dhvaṁsati||he falls to dust|lang=sa}}). For semantic development compare {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|animalis||animal|lang=la}}, from {{term|anima||breath, spirit|lang=la}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|pl= '''deer''' ''or dated and rare'', '''[[deers]]'''}}
{{wikipedia}}

# {{context|zoology}} a ruminant mammal with [[antler]]s and [[hoof|hooves]] of the family ''[[Cervidae]]'' or one of several similar animals from related families of the order ''[[Artiodactyla]]''
#: ''I wrecked my car after a '''deer''' ran across the road.''
# The [[meat]] of such an animal
#: ''Oh I've never had '''deer''' before.''
# {{archaic}} Any animal, especially a mammal.
#: ''But mice and rats and such small '''deer''', have been Tom's food for seven long year.'' -Shakespeare, King Lear. Act III. Sc. IV.

